A Phase I Environmental Site Assessment (ESA) was performed by Vieau Associates, Inc. in
November 2012. The following are excerpts from that report:
Historical Land Use: Historical records indicate that the subject property consisted of
cultivated agricultural land by at least 1937. The property was left vacant and fallow by the
late 1950s and remained vacant until the original por ion of the former industrial building
was constructed in 1969. Additions were constructed onto the building in 1983 and 1987.
Since construction the property was occupied by LaMaur, Dow Brands, and Electronic Hair
Styling as manufacturers of shampoo, hair rinses, lotions, hair spray and cremes. From
1987 until 1995, the property also manufactured cleaning supplies. Operations ceased in
the mid 2000s and the industrial building was removed in 2006. The property currently
consists of vacant land with no improvements.
Prior Investigations: Based on the historical industrial land use, several environmental
assessments have been completed for the property since 1996. These prior investigations
have documented contamination in soil and groundwater across the site. Sources of
contamination appear to have included tanks, spills, and general manufacturing and waste
generation activities from beauty product and cleaning supply manufacturing activities.
These activities occurred from 1969 when the building was constructed until the mid 2000s
when operations ceased at the property. At least eight chemical spills were reported to the
MPCA between 1996 and 2007; precise locations of the spills were not documented. A total
of 29 petroleum and chemical underground and aboveground storage tanks were
registered at the property (all reportedly removed prior to building demolition).
Based on recent investigation data, VOC vapors were detected in soil above MPCA action
levels, and alcohols and volatile organic compounds were detected in the soil and or
groundwater at the site. Methanol, 1,1-Dichloroethane and n-Butanol were the only
compounds detected in groundwater above Minnesota Department of Health (MDH) Health
Risk Limits (HRLs). The "Identified Release" was defined by the MPCA in 2007 (Exhibit A)
and can be found in Appendix F.
We view the presence of contamination at the site as a recognized environmental condition
Conclusions: We have per ormed a Phase I environmental site assessment in general
conformance with the scope and limitations of ASTM Practice E 1527-05 of the property
identified by the address 5601 East River Road Northeast, Fridley, Minnesota, 55432. Any
exceptions to, or deletions from, this practice are described in Section 2.4 of this report.
This assessment has revealed no evidence of recognized environmental conditions in
connection with the property, except the following:
• Prior investigation at the property has documented contamination in soil and
groundwater across the si e. Based on recent investigation data, VOC vapors were
detected in soil above MPCA action levels, and alcohols and volatile organic
compounds were detected in the soil and/or groundwater at the site. Methanol, 1 1-
Dichloroethane and n-Butanol were the only compounds detec ed in groundwater
above Minnesota Department of Health (MDH) Health Risk Limits (HRLs). We view the
presence of contamination at the site as a recognized environmental condition (REC).
The term recognized environmental conditions means the presence or likely presence
of any hazardous substances or petroleum products on a property under conditions
that indicate an existing release, a past release, or a material threat of a release of
any hazardous subs ances or petroleum products into structures on the property or
into the ground, ground water or surface water of the property. The term includes
hazardous substances or petroleum products even under conditions in compliance
with laws. The term is not intended to include de minimis conditions that generally do
not present a threat to human health or the environment and that generally would
not be the subject of an enforcement action if brought to the atten on of appropriate
governmental agencies. Conditions determined to be de minimis are not recognized
Recommendations: The site should be re-enrolled in the VIC and Petroleum Brownfields
programs, and a Response Action Plan and Construction Contingency Plan (RAP CCP)
should be submitted for review and app oval by the Minnesota Pollution Control Agency
(MPCA) based on the prior detection of both petroleum and non-petroleum compounds.
The RAP CCP will summarize the environmental impac s known to be present, how
contaminated soil will be managed, how human health will be protected, and con ingencies
if unexpected conditions or contamination is encountered.
Based on the limited screening to date, no obvious indications of significant con amination
that would warrant offsite disposal were encountered; however the developer should be
prepared to p operly manage contaminated soil if or when it is encountered.
No other issues of environmental concern were identified in connection with the property.

Nearly all of the proposed impervious surface will be collected and routed to these ponds, which

Also proposed is a small rain garden along the south side of the central corridor street. This rain

A Traffic Impact Studay was completed by
Spack Consulting on April 25, 2013, and is included
in its entirety in Appendix C. Below is the executive summary:
Background: Industrial Equities is proposing a speculative office/warehouse building north
of Interstate 694 and east of East River Road in Fridley, MN. In addition to the proposed
134,192 square foot office/warehouse building, the City of Fridley has guided the western
portion of the vacant site for a 311,650 square foot office building and 120 unit senior
living apartment complex. This study analyzed the proposed development to identify
potential traffic operations issues and recommend improvements if needed.
Build 1 consists of adding the traffic from the office/warehouse building to the No-
Build 2 consists of Build 1 plus traffic generated by the other office building and
senio housing complex at the site
Build 3 consists of Build 2 plus traffic generated by the proposed BAE Systems
redevelopment along East River Road on the south side of Interstate 694. This is a
recently proposed large industrial development that could impact the
transportation network being analyzed in this study. The additional traffic volumes
from this development are based on the Traffic Impact Study – Industrial Park in
Results: The traffic impacts of the proposed development on the site’s driveway
intersections as well as the public road intersections along East River Road at the I-694
Interchange, 57th Avenue and 61st Way were analyzed for multiple future scenarios. The
i. The full site is anticipated to generate approximately 2,400 entering/2,400 exi ing
vehicles on a daily basis, 530 entering/100 exiting vehicles during the a.m. peak hour
and 120 entering/490 exiting vehicles during the p.m peak hour. The proposed
office/warehouse building will generate approximately one fifth of the site’s traff c.
ii. All study intersections are forecast to operate acceptably at Level of Service B or
better in the 2015 Build peak hour scenarios.
iii. The I-694 & East River Road Interchange will need to be reconstructed if the BAE
Systems Industrial Park redevelopment is fully implemented (see the Traffic Impact
Study – Industrial Park in Fridley, MN dated January 25, 2013). A fully reconstructed
interchange could be built to also accommodate the traffic from the proposed
iv. The East River Road & 57th Avenue intersection is forecast to operate
unacceptably in all of the 2033 a.m peak hour scenarios as well as the p.m peak
hour in the 2033 Build 2 and Build 3 scenarios. An additional westbound to
southbound left turn lane would allow the intersection to operate acceptably through
the 2033 a.m peak hour No-Build and Build 1 scenarios as well as all of the p m
peak scenarios. To mitigate all of the po ential Build scenarios, East River Road would
need to be upgraded to a six lane facility. Appropriate public right-of-way is dedicated
to allow for these possible future expansions along East River Road and 57th Avenue.
Recommendations: Updating the signal timing along East River Road is recommended
after each phase of development is fully operational Building 57th Avenue per the
proposed development plan is sufficien for the office/warehouse portion of the
development. The East River Road & 57th Avenue intersection should be analyzed again
for poten ial improvements when the senior housing/office building plans are proposed or
when the 57th Avenue extension east of the site is planned, whichever comes first.

RE: Natural Heritage Review of the proposed Riverside Business Centre;
As requested, the above project has been reviewed for potential effects to known occurrences of rare
features. A search of the Minnesota Natural Heritage Information System did identify rare features within an
approximate one-mile radius of the proposed project, but these records did not include any federally listed
species and were either historical or not of concern given the project details that were provided with the data
request form. As such, I do not believe the proposed project will adversely affect any known occurrences of rare
The Natural Heritage Information System (NHIS), a collection of databases that contains information
about Minnesota’s rare natural features, is maintained by the Division of Ecological and Water Resources,
Department of Natural Resources. The NHIS is continually updated as new information becomes available, and
is the most complete source of data on Minnesota's rare or otherwise significant species, native plant
communities, and other natural features. However, the NHIS is not an exhaustive inventory and thus does not
represent all of the occurrences of rare features within the state. Therefore, ecologically significant features for
which we have no records may exist within the project area.
For environmental review purposes, the results of this Natural Heritage Review are valid for one year;
the results are only valid for the project location (noted above) and project description provided on the NHIS
Data Request Form. Please contact me if project details change or if an updated review is needed.
Please note that locations of the gray wolf (
Canis lupus), state-listed as special concern, and the Canada
Lynx canadensis), federally-listed as threatened, are not currently tracked in the NHIS. As such, the
Natural Heritage Review does not address these species.
Furthermore, the Natural Heritage Review does not constitute review or approval by the Department of
Natural Resources as a whole. Instead, it identifies issues regarding known occurrences of rare features and
potential effects to these rare features. Additional rare features for which we have no data may be present in the
project area, or there may be other natural resource concerns associated with the proposed project. For these
concerns, please contact your DNR Regional Environmental Assessment Ecologist (contact information available
). Please be aware that additional site
assessments or review may be required.
Thank you for consulting us on this matter, and for your interest in preserving Minnesota's rare natural
resources. An invoice will be mailed to you under separate cover.

Industrial Equities is proposing a speculative office/warehouse building north of

plan for the entire site is shown in the Appendix.

currently proposed. For purposes of this study, it is assumed the full
development will be built and occupied within twenty years.

East River Road is classified as Anoka County State Aid Highway 1 near

mph speed limit near the site.

limit. It will be extended to the east as part of the project and the
preliminary design is shown on the site plan in the Appendix.

in this study because it is the first traffic signal controlled intersection on
East River Road north of the proposed site.
